This Python session will explore the i.i.d. financial models, starting from the basics and exploring more advanced topics like shrinkage estimators and robust estimators to heavy tails.

Financial data

We will now explore financial data to see whether it is really heavy-tailed.

We can conclude that financial data is clearly heavy-tailed. Therefore, using the classical sample estimators is probably going to be pretty bad, which we will explore next.

Classical estimators

Letâs warm up using the classical estimators for the mean and covariance matrix, namely the sample mean and the sample covariance matrix: \[ \begin{aligned} \boldsymbol{\mu} & = \frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^T\mathbf{x}_t\\ \boldsymbol{\Sigma} & = \frac{1}{T-1}\sum_{t=1}^T(\mathbf{x}_t-\boldsymbol{\mu})(\mathbf{x}_t-\boldsymbol{\mu})^T. \end{aligned} \]

# generate Gaussian synthetic return data
import numpy as np

np.random.seed(42)
N = 200
T = 500
mu = np.zeros(N)
U = np.random.multivariate_normal(mean=mu, cov=0.1*np.eye(N), size=round(.7*N)).T
Sigma_cov = U @ U.T + np.eye(N)
X = np.random.multivariate_normal(mean=mu, cov=Sigma_cov, size=T)

mu_classical = np.mean(X, axis=0) # classical mean estimator (sample mean)
np.linalg.norm(mu_classical - mu)
#> 2.2388459756304293
Sigma_classical = np.cov(X.T) # classical covariance estimator (sample covariance matrix)
np.linalg.norm(Sigma_classical - Sigma_cov) / np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov)
#> 0.43096917656413286

Data with outliers

Now, letâs add some of outliers in the data and see how the performance degrades significantly.

np.random.seed(42)

Sigma_scm    = np.cov(X_outliers[:50,:].T)

# define function to draw an ellipse from a covariance matrix
def confidence_ellipse(cov, mean, ax, facecolor='none', **kwargs):
    from matplotlib.patches import Ellipse
    import matplotlib.transforms as transforms
    values, vectors = np.linalg.eig(cov)
    angle = np.arccos(vectors[0, 0]) * 180 / np.pi
    ellipse = Ellipse((mean[0], mean[1]),
        width=values[0],
        height=values[1],
        facecolor=facecolor,
        **kwargs)
    mean_x, mean_y = mean    
    transf = transforms.Affine2D().rotate_deg(angle)
    ellipse.set_transform(transf + ax.transData)
    return ellipse

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5, 5))

Heavy-tailed data

Letâs now generate heavy-tailed synthetic data and see the performance of the classical sample estimators.

np.random.seed(42)
# generate heavy-tailed synthetic return data
nu = 4  # degrees of freedom (measures how heavy the tail is)
N = 200
T = 500
mu = np.zeros(N)
U = np.random.multivariate_normal(mean=mu, cov=0.1*np.eye(N), size=round(.7*N)).T
Sigma_cov = U @ U.T + np.eye(N)

def multivariate_t(mean, cov, nu=np.inf, size=1):
    '''generate random variables of multivariate t distribution
    '''
    mean = np.asarray(mean)
    d = len(mean)
    if nu == np.inf:
        x = 1.
    else:
        x = np.random.chisquare(nu, size) / nu
    z = np.random.multivariate_normal(np.zeros(d), cov, (size,))
    return mean + z/np.sqrt(x)[:,None]

X = multivariate_t(mean=mu, cov=(nu-2)/nu*Sigma_cov, nu=nu, size=T)  

# classical mean estimators
mu_classical = np.mean(X, axis=0)
np.linalg.norm(mu_classical - mu)
#> 2.33578097421874
Sigma_classical = np.cov(X.T)
np.linalg.norm(Sigma_classical - Sigma_cov) / np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov)

# keep two variables for the 2D scatter plots
#> 0.7054800812539801
i1 = 2
i2 = 180
X = X[:, [i1, i2]]
N = X.shape[1]

Factor models

Macroeconomic factor model

Single market factor

We will start with a simple example consisting of a single known factor (i.e., the market index). The model is \[ \mathbf{x}_t = \boldsymbol{\alpha} + \boldsymbol{\beta}f_t + \boldsymbol{\epsilon}_t, \quad t=1,\ldots,T \] where the explicit factor \(f_t\) is the S&P 500 index. We will do a simple least squares (LS) regression to estimate the intercept \(\boldsymbol{\alpha}\) and the loading beta \(\boldsymbol{\beta}\): \[ \underset{\boldsymbol{\alpha},\boldsymbol{\beta}}{\text{minimize}}\quad \sum_{t=1}^T\|\mathbf{x}_t - \boldsymbol{\alpha} - \boldsymbol{\beta}f_t\|^2 \]

Most the code lines go into preparing the data rather than actually performing the factor modeling. Letâs start getting the data ready:Ã¥

# compute the log-returns of the stocks and of the SP500 index as explicit factor
X = dataset[['Adj Close']].apply(np.log).apply(np.diff).xs('Adj Close',axis=1)  # ?pandas.DataFrame.xs
T, N = X.shape  # number of days, number of stocks
f = sp500[['Adj Close']].apply(np.log).apply(np.diff).xs('Adj Close', axis=1)

Now we are ready to do the factor model fitting. The solution to the previous LS fitting is \[ \begin{aligned} \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} & = {\sf cov}(\mathbf{x}_t,f_t)/{\sf var}(f_t)\\ \hat{\boldsymbol{\alpha}} & = \bar{x} - \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}\bar{f}\\ \hat{\boldsymbol{\epsilon}}_i & = \mathbf{x}_i - \alpha_i\mathbf{1} - \beta_i\mathbf{f}, \quad i=1,\ldots,N\\ \hat{\sigma}_i^2 & = \frac{1}{T-2}\hat{\boldsymbol{\epsilon}}_i^T\hat{\boldsymbol{\epsilon}}_i, \quad \hat{\boldsymbol{\Psi}} = \sf{diag}(\hat{\sigma}_1^2, \ldots, \hat{\sigma}_N^2)\\ \hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}} & = {\sf var}(f_t)\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}^T + \hat{\boldsymbol{\Psi}} \end{aligned} \] which can be readily implemented in Python as follows

import pandas as pd

beta_vec = np.array([np.cov(X[stock], y=f)[0, 1]/np.cov(f, f)[0, 0] for stock in X.columns]).reshape((N, -1))
beta = pd.DataFrame(beta_vec.reshape((-1, N)), columns = stock_namelist)
alpha = X.mean() - beta * f.mean()
sigma2 = np.zeros(N)
for stock, k in zip(X.columns, range(len(X.columns))):
  eps_i = X[stock] - np.asarray(alpha[stock]) - np.asarray(beta[stock])*f
  sigma2[k] = np.dot(eps_i, eps_i.T) / (T-2)
Psi_mat = np.diag(sigma2)
Sigma_mat = np.cov(f, f)[0, 0] * beta_vec @ beta_vec.T + Psi_mat
Psi = pd.DataFrame(Psi_mat, columns = stock_namelist)
Sigma = pd.DataFrame(Sigma_mat, columns = stock_namelist)
print(alpha)
#>           A        AA      AAPL  ...      AMD       APD        CF
#> 0  0.000064  0.001114  0.000269  ...  0.00156 -0.000499 -0.000626
#> 
#> [1 rows x 9 columns]
print(beta)

Alternatively, we can do the fitting using a more compact matrix notation (recall time is along the vertical axis in \(\mathbf{X}\)) \[ \mathbf{X}^T = \boldsymbol{\alpha}\mathbf{1}^T + \boldsymbol{\beta}\mathbf{f}^T + \mathbf{E}^T \] and then write the LS fitting as \[ \underset{\boldsymbol{\alpha},\boldsymbol{\beta}}{\text{minimize}}\quad \|\mathbf{X}^T - \boldsymbol{\alpha}\mathbf{1}^T - \boldsymbol{\beta}\mathbf{f}^T\|^2_F. \] More conveniently, we can define \(\boldsymbol{\Gamma} = [ \boldsymbol{\alpha}, \boldsymbol{\beta} ]\) and the extended factors \(\tilde{\mathbf{F}} = [\mathbf{1}, \mathbf{f}]\). The LS formulation can then be written as \[ \underset{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}{\text{minimize}}\quad \|\mathbf{X}^T - \boldsymbol{\Gamma}\tilde{\mathbf{F}}^T\|^2_F \] with solution \[ \boldsymbol{\Gamma} = \mathbf{X}^T \tilde{\mathbf{F}} (\tilde{\mathbf{F}}^T \tilde{\mathbf{F}})^{-1} \]

F_ = np.column_stack([np.ones(len(f)), f])
Gamma_mat = np.linalg.solve(F_.T @ F_, F_.T @ X)
Gamma = pd.DataFrame(Gamma_mat.T, columns = ["alpha", "beta"])
alpha = Gamma["alpha"]
beta = Gamma["beta"]
print(Gamma)
#>       alpha      beta
#> 0  0.000281  1.327718
#> 1  0.000643  1.859352
#> 2  0.000400  1.095790
#> 3  0.000668  0.902275
#> 4  0.000361  1.268304
#> 5 -0.002209  1.711576
#> 6  0.001383  2.173830
#> 7  0.000150  1.027058
#> 8 -0.000626  1.571276
E = (np.asarray(X.T) - np.asarray(Gamma @ F_.T)).T
Psi = E.T @ E / (T - 2)
Sigma = np.cov(f, f)[0, 0] * np.asarray(beta).T @ np.asarray(beta) + np.diag(np.diag(Psi_mat))

As expected, we get the same result regardless of the notation used.

Assessing investment funds

In this example, we will assess the performance of several investment funds based on factor models. We will use the S&P 500 as the explicit market factor and assume a zero risk-free return \(r_f=0\). In particular, we will consider the following six Exchange-Traded Funds (ETFs):

  • SPY - SPDR S&P 500 ETF (index tracking)
  • XIVH - Velocity VIX Short Vol Hedged (high alpha)
  • SPHB - PowerShares S&P 500 High Beta Portfolio (high beta)
  • SPLV - PowerShares S&P 500 Low Volatility Portfolio (low beta)
  • USMV - iShares Edge MSCI Min Vol USA ETF
  • JKD - iShares Morningstar Large-Cap ETF

Some observations are now in order:

  • SPY is an ETF that follows the S&P 500 and, as expected, it has an alpha almost zero and a beta almost one: \(\alpha=7.7\times10^{-5}\) and \(\beta=1.006\).
  • XIVH is an ETF with a high alpha and indeed the alpha computed is the highest among the ETFs (1-2 orders of magnitude higher): \(\alpha=1.885\times10^{-3}\).
  • SPHB is an ETF supposedly with a high beta and the computed beta is among the hightest, but not the highest: \(\beta=1.56\). Interestingly, the computed alpha is negative! So this ETF seems to be dangerous and caution should be taken.
  • SPLV is an ETF that aims at having a low volatility and indeed the computed beta is on the low side: \(\beta=0.68\).
  • USMV is also an ETF that aims at having a low volatility and indeed the computed beta is the lowest: \(\beta=0.66\).
  • JKD seems not to be extreme and shows a good tradeof.

Statistical factor model

Letâs now consider statistical factor models or implicit factor models where both the factors and the loadings are not available. Recall the principal factor method for the model \(\mathbf{X}^T = \boldsymbol{\alpha}\mathbf{1}^T + \mathbf{B}\mathbf{F}^T + \mathbf{E}^T\) with \(K\) factors:

  1. PCA:
    • sample mean: \(\hat{\boldsymbol{\alpha}} = \bar{\mathbf{x}} = \frac{1}{T}\mathbf{X}^T\mathbf{1}_T\)
    • demeaned matrix: \(\bar{\mathbf{X}} = \mathbf{X} - \mathbf{1}_T\bar{\mathbf{x}}^T\)
    • sample covariance matrix: \(\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}} = \frac{1}{T-1}\bar{\mathbf{X}}^T\bar{\mathbf{X}}\)
    • eigen-decomposition: \(\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}} = \hat{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}} \hat{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}} \hat{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}^T\)
  2. Estimates:
    • \(\hat{\mathbf{B}} = \hat{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}_1} \hat{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}}_1^{1/2}\)
    • \(\hat{\boldsymbol{\Psi}} = {\sf Diag}\left(\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}} - \hat{\mathbf{B}} \hat{\mathbf{B}}^T\right)\)
    • \(\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}} = \hat{\mathbf{B}} \hat{\mathbf{B}}^T + \hat{\boldsymbol{\Psi}}\)
  3. Update the eigen-decomposition: \(\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}} - \hat{\boldsymbol{\Psi}} = \hat{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}} \hat{\boldsymbol{\Lambda}} \hat{\boldsymbol{\Gamma}}^T\)
  4. Repeat Steps 2-3 until convergence.
from sklearn.preprocessing import scale

K = 3
alpha = np.mean(X, axis=0)
X_ = scale(X, with_std=False)
Sigma_prev = np.zeros((N, N))
Psi = np.zeros((N, N))
Sigma = X_.T @ X_ / (T-1)
while (np.linalg.norm(Sigma - Sigma_prev)/np.linalg.norm(Sigma) > 1e-3):
  values, vectors = np.linalg.eig(Sigma - Psi)
  B = vectors[:, :K] * np.sqrt(values[:K])
  Psi = np.diag(np.diag(Sigma - B @ B.T))
  Sigma_prev = Sigma
  Sigma = B @ B.T + Psi

Shrinkage estimators

This section will illustrate the incorporation of prior information in the estimation of \(\boldsymbol{\mu}\) and \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\).

Suppose we have an \(N\)-dimensional i.i.d. Gaussian time series \[ \mathbf{x}_t \sim \mathcal{N}(\boldsymbol{\mu}, \boldsymbol{\Sigma}). \] The sample estimators for the mean and covariance matrix are, respectively, the sample mean \[ \hat{\boldsymbol{\mu}} = \frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^T \mathbf{x}_t \] and the sample covariance matrix \[ \hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}} = \frac{1}{T-1}\sum_{t=1}^T (\mathbf{x}_t - \hat{\boldsymbol{\mu}})^T(\mathbf{x}_t - \hat{\boldsymbol{\mu}}). \] We will next explore the idea of shrinkage in order to improve those sample estimators when \(T\) is not large enough.

Shrinkage for \(\boldsymbol{\mu}\)

The James-Stein estimator is \[ \hat{\boldsymbol{\mu}}^\textsf{JS} = (1-\rho) \hat{\boldsymbol{\mu}} + \rho \mathbf{t} \] where \(\mathbf{t}\) is the shrinkage target and \(0\le\rho\le1\) is the amount of shrinkage. Common choices for the target \(\mathbf{t}\) are:

  • \(\mathbf{t} = \mathbf{0}\)
  • \(\mathbf{t} = 0.1 \times \mathbf{1}\)
  • \(\mathbf{t} = \frac{\mathbf{1}^T \hat{\boldsymbol{\mu}}}{N} \times \mathbf{1}\) (grand mean target)
  • \(\mathbf{t} = \frac{\mathbf{1}^T\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^{-1}\hat{\boldsymbol{\mu}}}{\mathbf{1}^T\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^{-1}\mathbf{1}} \times \mathbf{1}\) (volatility-weighted mean)

A choice of \(\rho\) that improves the estimatior error is \[ \rho = \frac{1}{T}\frac{N\bar{\boldsymbol{\lambda}}-2\boldsymbol{\lambda}_\textsf{max}}{\|\hat{\boldsymbol{\mu}} - \mathbf{t}\|^2} \] where \(\bar{\boldsymbol{\lambda}}\) and \(\boldsymbol{\lambda}_\textsf{max}\) are the average and maximum values, respectively, of the eigenvalues of \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\) (or \(\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}\)).

We will first explore this estimator using synthetic data. Letâs start generating the data:

# generate Gaussian synthetic return data
np.random.seed(42)
N = 100
T = 120
mu = np.random.uniform(size=N)
U = np.random.multivariate_normal(mean=np.zeros(N), cov=0.1*np.eye(N), size=round(0.7*N)).T
Sigma = U @ U.T + np.eye(N)
X = np.random.multivariate_normal(mean=mu, cov=Sigma, size=T)

# sample estimates (sample mean and sample covariance matrix)
mu_sm     = np.mean(X, axis=0)
Sigma_scm = np.cov(X.T)

Now letâs try the James-Stein estimator with the four targets:

# define the four targets
t_1 = np.zeros(N)
t_2 = 0.1 * np.ones(N)
t_3 = np.mean(mu_sm) * np.ones(N)
t_4 = np.sum(np.linalg.solve(Sigma_scm, mu_sm)/np.sum(np.linalg.solve(Sigma_scm, np.ones(N))))*np.ones(N)

# compute the corresponding four rho's
lambdas, _ = np.linalg.eig(Sigma_scm)
lmd_mean = np.mean(lambdas)
lmd_max = np.max(lambdas)
rho_1 = (1/T)*(N*lmd_mean - 2*lmd_max)/np.linalg.norm(mu_sm - t_1)**2
rho_2 = (1/T)*(N*lmd_mean - 2*lmd_max)/np.linalg.norm(mu_sm - t_2)**2
rho_3 = (1/T)*(N*lmd_mean - 2*lmd_max)/np.linalg.norm(mu_sm - t_3)**2
rho_4 = (1/T)*(N*lmd_mean - 2*lmd_max)/np.linalg.norm(mu_sm - t_4)**2

# finally the James-Stein estimators
mu_JS_1 = (1-rho_1)*mu_sm + rho_1*t_1
mu_JS_2 = (1-rho_2)*mu_sm + rho_2*t_2
mu_JS_3 = (1-rho_3)*mu_sm + rho_3*t_3
mu_JS_4 = (1-rho_4)*mu_sm + rho_4*t_4

Letâs now compare the estimation error measured in terms of squared error and PRIAL (percentage relative improvement in average loss): \[ \begin{align} \textsf{SE} &= \|\hat{\boldsymbol{\mu}}^\textsf{JS} - \boldsymbol{\mu}\|^2\\ \textsf{PRIAL} &= \frac{\|\hat{\boldsymbol{\mu}} - \boldsymbol{\mu}\|^2 - \|\hat{\boldsymbol{\mu}}^\textsf{JS} - \boldsymbol{\mu}\|^2}{\|\hat{\boldsymbol{\mu}} - \boldsymbol{\mu}\|^2} \end{align} \]

# compute squared error and PRIAL
SE_mu = np.array([np.linalg.norm(mu_sm   - mu)**2,
                  np.linalg.norm(mu_JS_1 - mu)**2,
                  np.linalg.norm(mu_JS_2 - mu)**2,
                  np.linalg.norm(mu_JS_3 - mu)**2,
                  np.linalg.norm(mu_JS_4 - mu)**2])
names = ["sample mean", "JS with 0 target", "JS with 0.1 target", 
         "JS with GM target", "JS with VW target"]
ref = np.linalg.norm(mu_sm - mu)**2
PRIAL_mu = (ref - SE_mu)/ref

# plots
pd.DataFrame(SE_mu.reshape((-1, 5)), columns=names).plot.barh(title="Squared error on the estimation of mu")
#> <AxesSubplot: title={'center': 'Squared error on the estimation of mu'}>
plt.show()

pd.DataFrame(PRIAL_mu.reshape((-1, 5)), columns=names).plot.barh(title="PRIAL on the estimation of mu")
#> <AxesSubplot: title={'center': 'PRIAL on the estimation of mu'}>
plt.show()

The improvement in performance is quite clear. We can now plot the error as a function of the number of samples to get a more complete picture:

Shrinkage for \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\)

The shrinkage estimator for the covariance matrix is \[ \hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^\textsf{sh} = (1-\rho) \hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}} + \rho \mathbf{T} \] where \(\mathbf{T}\) is the shrinkage target and \(0\le\rho\le1\) is the amount of shrinkage.

Common choices for the target \(\mathbf{T}\) are:

  • \(\mathbf{T} = \frac{1}{N}\textsf{Tr}\left(\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}\right) \times \mathbf{I}\) (scaled identity)
  • \(\mathbf{T} = \textsf{Diag}(\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}})\) (diagonal)

To determine \(\rho\) we will use three different criteria via random matrix theory (RMT):

  • MSE of covariance matrix
  • quadratic loss of precision matrix
  • Sharpe ratio.

Letâs start by generating some synthetic data:

# generate Gaussian synthetic return data
np.random.seed(42)
N = 100
T = 120
mu = np.random.uniform(size=N)
U = np.random.multivariate_normal(mean=np.zeros(N), cov=0.1*np.eye(N), size=round(0.7*N)).T
Sigma = U @ U.T + np.eye(N)
X = np.random.multivariate_normal(mean=mu, cov=Sigma, size=T)

# sample estimates (sample mean and sample covariance matrix)
mu_sm     = np.mean(X, axis=0)
Sigma_scm = np.cov(X.T)

The two targets are easily computed:

# two target matrices T=Identity and T=Diagonal
T_I = np.sum(np.diag(Sigma_scm))/N * np.eye(N)
T_D = np.diag(np.diag(Sigma_scm))

Ledoit-Wolf shrinkage

We next compute the Ledoit-Wolf estimator: \[ \rho =\min\left(1,\frac{\frac{1}{T^{2}}\sum_{t=1}^{T}||\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}-\mathbf{r}_{t}\mathbf{r}_{t}^{T}||_{F}^{2}}{||\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}-\mathbf{T}||_{F}^{2}}\right) \]

# Ledoit-Wolf shrinkage estimators with two targets 
def rho_LW(X, Sigma_scm, Sigma_T):
    X = scale(X, with_std=False)
    T = X.shape[0]
    tmp = (1-T)*np.linalg.norm(Sigma_scm)**2 + np.sum(np.apply_along_axis(np.linalg.norm, 1, X)**4)
    rho = np.min([1, (1./T**2) * tmp / np.linalg.norm(Sigma_scm - Sigma_T)**2])
    return rho

rho = rho_LW(X, Sigma_scm, T_I)
Sigma_LW_I = (1-rho)*Sigma_scm + rho*T_I
rho = rho_LW(X, Sigma_scm, T_D)
Sigma_LW_D = (1-rho)*Sigma_scm + rho*T_D

Letâs now compare the estimation error measured in terms of squared error and PRIAL: \[ \begin{align} \textsf{SE} &= \|\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^\textsf{sh} - \boldsymbol{\Sigma}\|_F^2\\ \textsf{PRIAL} &= \frac{\|\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}} - \boldsymbol{\Sigma}\|_F^2 - \|\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^\textsf{sh} - \boldsymbol{\Sigma}\|_F^2}{\|\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}} - \boldsymbol{\Sigma}\|_F^2} \end{align} \]

# performance in terms of squared error and PRIAL
SE_Sigma = np.array([np.linalg.norm(Sigma_scm  - Sigma)**2,
                     np.linalg.norm(Sigma_LW_I - Sigma)**2,
                     np.linalg.norm(Sigma_LW_D - Sigma)**2])
names = ["SCM", "LW with I target", "LW with D target"]
ref = np.linalg.norm(Sigma_scm - Sigma)**2
PRIAL_Sigma = (ref - SE_Sigma) / ref

pd.DataFrame(SE_Sigma.reshape((-1, 3)), columns=names).plot.barh(title="Squared error on the estimation of Sigma")
#> <AxesSubplot: title={'center': 'Squared error on the estimation of Sigma'}>
plt.show()

pd.DataFrame(PRIAL_Sigma.reshape((-1, 3)), columns=names).plot.barh(title="PRIAL on the estimation of Sigma")
#> <AxesSubplot: title={'center': 'PRIAL on the estimation of Sigma'}>
plt.show()

Max-SR shrinkage

Letâs try now the shrinkage estimator based on maximizing the Sharpe ratio: \[ \begin{array}{ll} \underset{\rho_{1}\geq0}{\textsf{maximize}} & \begin{array}{c} \frac{\hat{\boldsymbol{\mu}}^{T}(\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^{\textsf{sh}})^{-1}\hat{\boldsymbol{\mu}}-\delta}{\sqrt{b\hat{\boldsymbol{\mu}}^{T}(\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^{\textsf{sh}})^{-1}\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}(\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^{\textsf{sh}})^{-1}\hat{\boldsymbol{\mu}}}}\end{array}\\ \textsf{subject to} & \begin{array}[t]{l} \hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^{\textsf{sh}}=\rho_{1}\mathbf{T}+\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}\\ \delta=D/(1-D)\\ D=\frac{1}{T}\textsf{Tr}(\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}(\hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}}^{\textsf{sh}})^{-1})\\ b=\frac{T}{\textsf{Tr}(\mathbf{W}(\mathbf{I}+\delta\mathbf{W})^{-2})} \end{array} \end{array} \] where \(\mathbf{W}=\mathbf{I}-\frac{1}{T}\mathbf{1}\mathbf{1}^{T}\).

def rho_maxSR(mu_sm, Sigma_scm, Sigma_T, T):
    W = np.eye(T) - np.ones(T*T).reshape((T, T))/T
    rho1_sweep = np.exp(np.linspace(-10, 10, 100))
    obj = []
    for rho1 in rho1_sweep:
        Sigma_sh = rho1 * Sigma_T + Sigma_scm
        D = (1/T)*np.sum(np.diag(Sigma_scm @ np.linalg.solve(Sigma_sh, np.eye(len(Sigma_sh)))))
        delta = D / (1 - D)
        B = np.linalg.solve((np.eye(T)+delta*W) @ (np.eye(T)+delta*W), np.eye(len(W)))
        b = T / np.sum(np.diag(W @ B))
        inv_S_sh_mu = np.linalg.solve(Sigma_sh, mu_sm).reshape((1, Sigma_sh.shape[0]))
        num = np.sum(mu_sm * inv_S_sh_mu) - delta
        den = np.sqrt(b * inv_S_sh_mu @ Sigma_scm @ inv_S_sh_mu.T)
        obj.append(num/den)
    i_max = np.argmax(obj)
    rho1 = rho1_sweep[i_max]
    return (rho1/(1 + rho1))

rho = rho_maxSR(mu_sm, Sigma_scm, T_I, T)
Sigma_maxSR_I = (1-rho)*Sigma_scm + rho*T_I
rho = rho_maxSR(mu_sm, Sigma_scm, T_D, T)
Sigma_maxSR_D = (1-rho)*Sigma_scm + rho*T_D

We can now evaluate the performance:

SE_Sigma = np.array([np.linalg.norm(Sigma_scm  - Sigma)**2,
                     np.linalg.norm(Sigma_maxSR_I - Sigma)**2,
                     np.linalg.norm(Sigma_maxSR_D - Sigma)**2])
names = ["SCM", "MAX-SR with I target", "MAX-SR with D target"]
ref = np.linalg.norm(Sigma_scm - Sigma)**2
PRIAL_Sigma = (ref - SE_Sigma) / ref

pd.DataFrame(SE_Sigma.reshape((-1, 3)), columns=names).plot.barh(title="Squared error on the estimation of Sigma")
#> <AxesSubplot: title={'center': 'Squared error on the estimation of Sigma'}>
plt.show()

pd.DataFrame(PRIAL_Sigma.reshape((-1, 3)), columns=names).plot.barh(title="PRIAL on the estimation of Sigma")
#> <AxesSubplot: title={'center': 'PRIAL on the estimation of Sigma'}>
plt.show()

Letâs also compute the Sharpe ratio:

def compute_SR(Sigma_scm, mu_sm, mu, Sigma):
    inv_S_sh_mu = np.linalg.solve(Sigma_scm, mu_sm).reshape((-1, len(Sigma_scm)))
    return np.sum(mu * inv_S_sh_mu) / np.sqrt(inv_S_sh_mu @ Sigma @ inv_S_sh_mu.T)

SR_Sigma = np.array([compute_SR(Sigma_scm, mu_sm, mu, Sigma),
                     compute_SR(Sigma_maxSR_I, mu_sm, mu, Sigma),
                     compute_SR(Sigma_maxSR_D, mu_sm, mu, Sigma)])

pd.DataFrame(SR_Sigma.reshape((-1, 3)), columns=names).plot.barh(title="Sharpe Ratio")
#> <AxesSubplot: title={'center': 'Sharpe Ratio'}>
plt.show()

Robust estimators to heavy tails

This section will illustrate the need for heavy-tailed estimators when it comes to financial data.

Estimator for \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\)

We will first consider the estimation of \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\) via Tylerâs estimator assuming that the mean is zero (or known and previously removed).

Recall that the sample covariance matrix is \[ \boldsymbol{\Sigma} = \frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^T\mathbf{x}_t\mathbf{x}_t^T \] whereas the Tyler estimator is the solution to the fixed-point equation: \[ \boldsymbol{\Sigma} = \frac{N}{T}\sum_{t=1}^T\frac{\mathbf{x}_t\mathbf{x}_t^T}{\mathbf{x}_t^T\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^{-1}\mathbf{x}_t}, \] which requires an iterative algorithm in practice.

Letâs code it in the following function:

def estimate_tyler(X, verbose=False):
    T, N = np.shape(X)
    max_iter = 100
    error_th_Sigma = 1e-3
    # Gaussian initial point
    Sigma = np.cov(X.T)  
    Sigma = Sigma/sum(np.diag(Sigma))
    #loop
    obj_value_record = np.empty(max_iter)
    Sigma_diff_record = np.empty(max_iter)
    for k in range(max_iter):
        Sigma_prev = np.copy(Sigma)
        # Tyler update
        Sigma_inv = np.linalg.solve(Sigma, np.eye(Sigma.shape[0]))
        weights = 1/np.diag(X @ Sigma_inv @ X.T)
        obj_value_record[k] = (N/2)*np.sum(np.log(weights)) - (T/2)*np.sum(np.log(np.linalg.eig(Sigma)[0].real))
        Sigma = (N/T) * X.T @ np.diag(weights) @ X
        Sigma = Sigma/np.sum(np.diag(Sigma))
        # stopping criterion
        Sigma_diff_record[k] = np.linalg.norm(Sigma - Sigma_prev) / np.linalg.norm(Sigma_prev)
        if (Sigma_diff_record[k] < error_th_Sigma):
            break
    obj_value_record = obj_value_record[:k]
    Sigma_diff_record = Sigma_diff_record[:k]
    # finally, recover missing scaling factor
    sigma2 = np.apply_along_axis(np.var, 0, X)
    d = np.diag(Sigma)
    kappa = np.sum(sigma2*d)/np.sum(d*d)
    if verbose:
        #sns.lineplot(np.arange(k), obj_value_record)
        plt.plot(np.arange(k), obj_value_record)
        plt.xlabel("Iterations")
        plt.ylabel("Objetive function")
        plt.show()
    return kappa*Sigma

np.random.seed(42)
N = 100
T = 300
mu = np.zeros(N)
U = np.random.multivariate_normal(mean=np.zeros(N), cov=0.1*np.eye(N), size=round(0.7*N)).T
Sigma_cov = U @ U.T + np.eye(N)
nu = 4
X = multivariate_t(mean=mu, cov=(nu-2)/nu*Sigma_cov, nu=nu, size=T)  

Sigma_tyler = estimate_tyler(X, verbose=True)

Sigma_classical = np.cov(X.T)

np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov - Sigma_tyler) / np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov)
#> 0.4178242612293536
np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov - Sigma_classical) / np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov)
#> 0.8844023458889887

It is now clear that Tylerâs estimator is much better than the naive sample covariance matrix when the data is heavy-tailed.

But what if the data was Gaussian? What would be the penalty for using Tyler when the sample covariance matrix would have been perfectly fine?

X = np.random.multivariate_normal(mean=mu, cov=Sigma_cov, size=T)
Sigma_tyler = estimate_tyler(X)
Sigma_classical = np.cov(X.T)

np.linalg.norm(Sigma - Sigma_tyler) / np.linalg.norm(Sigma)
#> 1.0796066830805728
np.linalg.norm(Sigma - Sigma_classical) / np.linalg.norm(Sigma)
#> 1.0781340031931597

Interestingly, we virtually donât really lose anything! So we better stick to heavy-tailed estimators all the time, just in case, just to be safe.

Estimator for \(\boldsymbol{\mu}\) and then \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\)

Now will consider the estimation of \(\boldsymbol{\mu}\) and then \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\) in two stages: first \(\boldsymbol{\mu}\) and then \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\) via Tylerâs estimator.

Letâs generate heavy-tailed data with a nonzero mean:

mu = np.random.normal(size=N)  # nonzero mean!
U = np.random.multivariate_normal(mean=np.zeros(N), cov=0.1*np.eye(N), size=round(0.7*N)).T
Sigma_cov = U @ U.T + np.eye(N)
X = multivariate_t(mean=mu, cov=(nu-2)/nu*Sigma_cov, nu=nu, size=T)  

# estimators assuming wrongly zero-mean
Sigma_classical = X.T @ X / (T - 1)
Sigma_tyler = estimate_tyler(X)

np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov - Sigma_tyler) / np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov)
#> 1.149183411686039
np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov - Sigma_classical) / np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov)
#> 0.9740460924030309

We need to demean or center the data. Letâs use the sample mean \[\boldsymbol{\mu} = \frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^T\mathbf{x}_t.\]

# let's remove the mean first
mu_classical = np.mean(X, axis=0)
np.linalg.norm(mu_classical - mu)
#> 1.458061761012409
X_ = X - mu_classical

# then estimate the covariance matrix
Sigma_classical = (1/(T-1)) * X_.T @ X_
Sigma_tyler = estimate_tyler(X_)
np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov - Sigma_tyler) / np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov)
#> 0.37832279285021864
np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov - Sigma_classical) / np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov)
#> 0.4987136705319818

However, the sample mean is not robust for heavy-tailed distributions, so we could use a robust estimator like the median:

# let's remove the median now
mu_median = np.median(X, axis=0)
np.linalg.norm(mu_median - mu)
#> 1.4467323844546998
X_ = X - mu_median

# then estimate the covariance matrix
Sigma_classical = X_.T @ X / (T-1)
Sigma_tyler = estimate_tyler(X_)
np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov - Sigma_tyler) / np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov)
#> 0.3775557992752501
np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov - Sigma_classical) / np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov)
#> 0.5088392776129118

We donât observe any significant improvement from using the median instead of the mean. We can try a more sophisticated robust estimation of the mean: the geometric median (aka spatial median).

The geometric median of a discrete set of sample points in a Euclidean space is the point minimizing the sum of distances to the sample points: \[\underset{\boldsymbol{\mu}}{\text{minimize}}\quad \sum_{t=1}^T\|\mathbf{x}_t-\boldsymbol{\mu}\|\] For the 1-dimensional case, it becomes the traditional median.

Letâs try the geometric median then:

from scipy.optimize import minimize
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist

def compute_geometric_median(X):
    return minimize(lambda x: cdist([x], X).sum(), np.mean(X, axis=0), method='powell').x

mu_gmedian = compute_geometric_median(X)
np.linalg.norm(mu_gmedian - mu)
#> 1.0772061757278562
X_ = X - mu_gmedian

# then estimate the covariance matrix
Sigma_classical = X_.T @ X / (T-1)
Sigma_tyler = estimate_tyler(X_)
np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov - Sigma_tyler) / np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov)
#> 0.3775893882670286
np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov - Sigma_classical) / np.linalg.norm(Sigma_cov)
#> 0.5030453970037209

The estimation of the \(\mathbf{\mu}\) has been significantly improved, but the estimation of the covariance matrix \(\mathbf{\Sigma}\) does not seem to be improved.

Joint Estimator for \(\boldsymbol{\mu}\) and \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\)

Until now, we have first estimated the mean vector (with estimators like the sample mean, median, and geometric median) and then the covariance matrix (with estimators like the sample covariance matrix and Tylerâs estimtor). In principle, this two-step procedure does not have to be optimal. We will now try a joint estimation of the mean vector and the covariance matrix under a heavy-tailed distribution via the Student-\(t\)âs maximum likelihood estimation (MLE). The algorithm becomes a bit more involved and we will not code it ourselves; instead we will use the R package fitHeavyTail.

library(fitHeavyTail)  # for Student-t estimation
library(mvtnorm)
library(reticulate)

# generate heavy-tailed synthetic return data
set.seed(237)
nu <- 4
N <- 200
T <- 300
mu <- rnorm(N)
U <- t(rmvnorm(n = round(0.7*N), sigma = 0.1*diag(N)))
Sigma_cov <- U %*% t(U) + diag(N)
X <- rmvt(n = T, delta = mu, sigma = (nu-2)/nu*Sigma_cov, df = nu)

# estimate the mean vector
mu_mean    <- colMeans(X)
mu_median  <- apply(X, 2, median)
mu_gmedian <- ICSNP::spatial.median(X)
norm(mu_mean    - mu, "2")
#> [1] 3.329964
norm(mu_median  - mu, "2")
#> [1] 3.230282
norm(mu_gmedian - mu, "2")
#> [1] 2.443257

# estimate the covariance matrix
Sigma_SCM <- cov(X)
norm(Sigma_SCM - Sigma_cov, "F")
#> [1] 300.798
  
X_ <- X - rep(mu_gmedian, each = T)
Sigma_tyler <- py$estimate_tyler(X_)
norm(Sigma_tyler - Sigma_cov, "F")
#> [1] 180.678

# joint estimation of mean vector and covariance matrix
fitted <- fit_mvt(X)
norm(fitted$mu - mu, "2")
#> [1] 2.29107
norm(fitted$cov - Sigma_cov, "F")
#> [1] 198.4872

Basically, both the estimation of the mean vector and covariance matrix are significantly improved.

Comparison

library(mvtnorm)  # for heavy-tailed generation
library(fitHeavyTail)  # for Student-t estimation

# parameters
set.seed(237)
nu <- 4
N <- 40
mu <- rnorm(N)
U <- t(rmvnorm(n = round(0.7*N), sigma = 0.1*diag(N)))
Sigma_cov <- U %*% t(U) + diag(N)

# main loop
T_sweep <- seq(from = 20, to = 600, by = 20)
error_mu_mean <- error_mu_median <- error_mu_gmedian <- error_mu_Student_t <- rep(NA, length(T_sweep))
error_Sigma_Tyler <- error_Sigma_Student_t <- error_Sigma_SCM <- rep(NA, length(T_sweep))
for(k in 1:length(T_sweep)) {
  T <- T_sweep[k]
  
  # generate heavy-tailed data
  X <- rmvt(n = T, delta = mu, sigma = (nu-2)/nu*Sigma_cov, df = nu)
  
  # estimation of mu
  mu_mean    <- colMeans(X)
  mu_median  <- apply(X, 2, median)
  mu_gmedian <- ICSNP::spatial.median(X)
  error_mu_mean[k]    <- norm(mu_mean    - mu, "2")
  error_mu_median[k]  <- norm(mu_median  - mu, "2")
  error_mu_gmedian[k] <- norm(mu_gmedian - mu, "2")
  
  # estimation of Sigma
  # SCM
  Sigma_SCM <- cov(X)
  error_Sigma_SCM[k] <- norm(Sigma_SCM - Sigma_cov, "F")
  
  # Tyler
  X_ <- X - rep(mu_gmedian, each = T)
  if (T > N) {
    Sigma_tyler <- py$estimate_tyler(X_)
    error_Sigma_Tyler[k] <- norm(Sigma_tyler - Sigma_cov, "F")
  }

  # Student-t
  if (T > N) {
    res_Student_t   <- fit_mvt(X)
    mu_Student_t    <- res_Student_t$mu
    Sigma_Student_t <- res_Student_t$cov
    error_Sigma_Student_t[k] <- norm(Sigma_Student_t - Sigma_cov, "F")
    error_mu_Student_t[k]    <- norm(mu_Student_t - mu, "2")
  }
}
library(ggplot2)
#> Keep up to date with changes at https://www.tidyverse.org/blog/
library(reshape2)

# plot error in mu
df_mu <- data.frame(T           = T_sweep, 
                    "mean"      = error_mu_mean, 
                    "median"    = error_mu_median, 
                    "gmedian"   = error_mu_gmedian, 
                    "Student-t" = error_mu_Student_t)
df_molten_mu <- melt(df_mu, id.vars = "T", variable.name = "method")
ggplot(df_molten_mu, aes(x = T, y = value, col = method, shape = method)) +
  geom_line() + geom_point(size = 2) +
  ggtitle(sprintf("Estimation error of mu (N = %d, nu = %d)", N, nu)) + ylab("error")

# plot error in Sigma
df_Sigma <- data.frame(T           = T_sweep, 
                       "SCM"       = error_Sigma_SCM, 
                       "Tyler"     = error_Sigma_Student_t, 
                       "Student-t" = error_Sigma_Tyler)
df_molten_Sigma <- melt(df_Sigma, id.vars = "T", variable.name = "method")
ggplot(df_molten_Sigma, aes(x = T, y = value, col = method, shape = method)) +
  geom_line() + geom_point(size = 2) +
  ggtitle(sprintf("Estimation error of Sigma (N = %d, nu = %d)", N, nu)) + ylab("error")

The final conclusion is clear: use a heavy-tailed estimator! Even better if the mean vector and covariance matrix are jointly estimated (see the R package fitHeavyTail).
